00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:28.555
PROFESSOR: Last time, we looked
at the case of a Bose gas,

00:00:28.555 --> 00:00:31.240
and we found that there
was this condensation

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:32.895
phenomena into the ground state.

00:00:36.710 --> 00:00:39.850
Let's go over it one more time.

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:43.420
So the idea was
that when you have

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:48.350
a Bose system, the occupation
of the different one-particle

00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:54.210
states, which you can specify
for a non-interacting system

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:58.990
in the grand canonical
ensemble, these entities

00:00:58.990 --> 00:01:03.240
are independent for each one
of the one-particle states

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:07.340
and have a form that is related
to the chemical potential

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:16.890
and the energy of these states
through this form, epsilon

00:01:16.890 --> 00:01:19.880
[? kd ?] in the
one-particle state,

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:25.100
and z standing for e to the
beta mu, chemical potential

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:27.950
divided by temperature.

00:01:27.950 --> 00:01:30.110
OK?

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:35.140
Now, if we go and look
at this in the limit

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:39.110
where z is much
less than 1, which

00:01:39.110 --> 00:01:41.530
is appropriate to
high temperatures

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:45.390
or when the case where the
gas is mostly classical,

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:46.680
you can expand this.

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:49.160
You can see that in
the lowest order,

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:53.270
it is z e to the minus
beta epsilon of k.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:57.840
So it looks like a
standard Boltzmann weight

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:01.540
that we would use in classical
statistical mechanics.

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:03.440
But then there are
higher order terms.

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:05.415
And in particular there
would be a correction

00:02:05.415 --> 00:02:10.130
that is e to the minus
beta epsilon of k squared

00:02:10.130 --> 00:02:15.270
and so forth that would
modify this result.

00:02:15.270 --> 00:02:17.910
But I think this is
something that I mentioned.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:22.790
If you look at a form such
as this at high temperatures,

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:24.970
it's like a Boltzmann weight.

00:02:24.970 --> 00:02:29.470
So the state that has
this lowest energy,

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:32.040
in this case if we
say epsilon of k

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:37.640
is h bar squared k squared
over 2m corresponding to k

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:40.360
equals to 0 for
the lowest energy,

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:46.244
has the highest mean
occupation number of weight.

00:02:46.244 --> 00:02:47.690
OK?

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:50.060
Now that is always the case.

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:54.310
This is a function
that, as epsilon of k

00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:57.610
becomes larger, no matter
whether you expand it or not,

00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:00.790
becomes less and less.

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:04.310
The other limit that
is of interest to us

00:03:04.310 --> 00:03:06.370
is how big can z be?

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:12.890
We said that the largest it
can be is when it approaches 1.

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:17.340
And when it is 1, this
quantity, the occupation number,

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:22.750
is e to the beta
epsilon of k minus 1.

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:27.650
Again, something that is
largest as k becomes smaller,

00:03:27.650 --> 00:03:31.050
and you go to the lowest energy.

00:03:31.050 --> 00:03:34.560
But there is the difficulty that
the one energy that corresponds

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:38.450
to k equals to 0, if I
look at this formula,

00:03:38.450 --> 00:03:41.300
it is 1 divided by 0.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:45.970
It just doesn't
make too much sense.

00:03:45.970 --> 00:03:49.130
Now, of course, we
said that typically we

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:54.490
don't want to work
in this variable.

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:56.730
We want to figure out
things as a function

00:03:56.730 --> 00:04:00.580
of the number of particles or
the number of particles divided

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:06.220
by volume density, which is
a nice intensive quantity.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:06.720
OK?

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:09.010
So typically, what should we do?

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:11.650
We said that in the
grand canonical ensemble,

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:19.930
N is the sum over k
these expectation values.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:22.060
I should really put
an average here,

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:24.820
but we said that in the
thermodynamic sense,

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:27.580
fluctuations being of the
order of square root of N,

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:29.074
we are going to ignore.

00:04:29.074 --> 00:04:30.490
So this is what
you would normally

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:34.530
call the number that
we have in the system.

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:41.240
And then you have to replace
this sum in the limit

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:44.420
where we have a large
system with an integral.

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:51.540
So we have the integral
d cubed k 2 pi cubed V.

00:04:51.540 --> 00:05:00.230
And then we have this N of k,
which is 1 over z inverse e

00:05:00.230 --> 00:05:03.710
to the beta epsilon
of k minus 1.

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:13.040
Now if I go like I did in
the line above to the limit

00:05:13.040 --> 00:05:17.650
where z is much less
than 1, then the integral

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:25.670
that I have to do is
simply the integral of z e

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:29.840
to the minus beta epsilon k
h bar squared k squared 2m.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:34.290
We know what this is.

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:37.520
This is simply, up
to a factor of z,

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:40.680
these are the integrals
that have given me

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:42.745
these factors of 1
over lambda cubed.

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:48.890
Actually, there's
the factor of V

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:51.004
here, so it is V
over lambda cubed.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:57.790
So normally, you would
then solve for z,

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:04.760
and you would find that z is
the density times lambda cubed.

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:08.450
And this is a formula that we
have seen a number of times,

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:14.356
that the chemical potential
is kt log of n lambda cubed.

00:06:14.356 --> 00:06:16.690
OK?

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:17.190
Fine.

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:19.140
But now we are interested
in the other limit.

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:26.791
Now in the other limit,
we have this difficulty

00:06:26.791 --> 00:06:32.430
that this quantity, if I look
at it as a function of z,

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:34.140
this is the quantity
that we would

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:40.420
call f-- it is
related to f 3/2 of z.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:48.080
So this is going to be 1 over
lambda cubed f 3/2 plus of z.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:07:00.560
It's a function that increases
with z up to the limiting value

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:04.240
that we are allowed to have,
which is at z equals to 1.

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:08.380
It's a function that starts
linearly, as we have discussed,

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:14.360
but then up here, it comes to
a finite value of zeta 3/2.

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:17.990
OK?

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:26.030
So basically, we know that when
I evaluate this for finite z,

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:28.730
I'm less than where I was here.

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:33.650
So this is certainly less
than 1 over lambda cubed zeta

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:36.970
of 3/2, the limiting value
that we have over here.

00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:42.730
So now I have a difficulty.

00:07:42.730 --> 00:07:50.710
This function over here,
I can only make it so big.

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:53.670
But I need to make
it big enough so

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:57.740
that I can put enough particles,
the total number of particles

00:07:57.740 --> 00:08:00.200
that I have in the system.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:02.720
So what is happening over here?

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:09.490
What is happening is that when
I make this density larger

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:13.730
and larger, ultimately
when I hit this point at z

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:17.470
equals to 1, as
we have discussed

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:23.160
there is an uncertainty as to
what happens to this expression

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:26.600
when z is equal to 1,
and you are at this state

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:30.020
that corresponds
to k equals to 0.

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:30.520
Right?

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:33.559
I don't know how many
things are over there.

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:36.400
So I can have, in
principle, the freedom

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:41.380
to take advantage of the fact
that I don't know what 1 over 0

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:47.950
is to call that the number
that I need to make up

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:51.342
the difference between
here and there.

00:08:51.342 --> 00:08:53.440
OK?

00:08:53.440 --> 00:09:02.460
And so, in principle,
when z goes to 1,

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:09.670
then this becomes 1 over lambda
cubed, or V over lambda cubed,

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:14.130
zeta of 3/2, obtained
by essentially

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:17.290
doing the integration
with z equals to 1,

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:21.280
evaluating it at
this possible limit.

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:25.580
And then whatever
is left, I will

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:29.560
put in the k equals to 0 state.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:30.610
OK?

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:35.070
And you will say, well, what
does that explicitly mean?

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:44.910
Well, what it means is that
I'm really evaluating things

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:50.620
at the value of z that
is extremely close to 1

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:54.290
so that in the thermodynamic
limit where N goes to infinity

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:57.240
I wouldn't know the difference.

00:09:57.240 --> 00:10:01.240
But it is really something
that vanishes only

00:10:01.240 --> 00:10:05.120
in that thermodynamic limit
of N going to infinity.

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:09.510
And we saw that if I kind
of look at the occupation

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:15.050
number of the k equals
to 0 state, what it is

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:27.220
is z inverse, which is e to
the minus beta mu minus 1.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:31.250
And if I'm in the limit
where z is very small,

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:36.650
or beta mu is-- sorry, z
is very much close to 1

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:41.430
or beta mu is very small,
then I can expand this.

00:10:41.430 --> 00:10:47.930
And this becomes approximately,
when mu goes to 0,

00:10:47.930 --> 00:10:49.718
minus 1 over beta mu.

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:55.230
OK?

00:10:55.230 --> 00:11:00.130
And I want this
to be the N0, what

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:05.040
is left over when I subtract
from the total number

00:11:05.040 --> 00:11:11.520
the amount that I can put
in to the ground state.

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:13.010
OK?

00:11:13.010 --> 00:11:17.820
And so you can see that this is
a quantity that is extensive.

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:21.130
It is proportional to
the number of particles.

00:11:21.130 --> 00:11:26.670
And mu is the inverse of
that, so it is infinitesimal.

00:11:26.670 --> 00:11:31.480
And if I choose that value
of mu that is, essentially,

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:35.540
pushing z infinitesimally
close to 1,

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:41.088
then I can ensure that I have
a finite occupation over there.

00:11:41.088 --> 00:11:43.020
OK?

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:44.150
So what does it mean?

00:11:44.150 --> 00:11:50.220
If I could actually look at
these occupation numbers,

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:58.070
then I am at temperatures
less than Tc of n.

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:00.010
And we saw that
basically we could

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.300
get what the temperature
is when this happens

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:11.180
by equating this combination
g over lambda cubed,

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:15.090
in principle, over-- I
had said g equals to 1.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:18.220
I could repeat it
with g not equal to 1.

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:26.210
And n, which is g over
lambda cubed zeta of 3/2,

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:29.640
rather than f 3/2 plus,
this defines for me

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:33.345
this temperature Tc of n.

00:12:33.345 --> 00:12:36.180
OK?

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:42.060
Now, if I could look at
the occupation numbers

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:46.070
when I was at temperature less
than Tc, what would I see?

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:52.520
I would see that the occupation
number as a function of k

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:56.230
is exactly the form that we
have over here with z equals

00:12:56.230 --> 00:13:07.830
to 1, 1 over e to the
beta epsilon of k minus 1.

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:11.870
But then at k
equals to 0, which I

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:16.370
can indicate by some
kind of delta function,

00:13:16.370 --> 00:13:20.360
I have everybody else,
which is this N minus

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:22.910
V over lambda cubed zeta of 3/2.

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:28.090
OK?

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:34.200
Actually, let's remember
that our k and momentum

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:36.650
are related to each other.

00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:42.620
So rather than asking
what the density is

00:13:42.620 --> 00:13:46.360
as a function of this
label k, I can maybe

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.350
ask what the density
is for things

00:13:49.350 --> 00:13:52.390
that have different momentum P.

00:13:52.390 --> 00:13:54.250
And according to
this formula, it

00:13:54.250 --> 00:14:00.000
is going to be beta P squared
over 2m, this kind of modified

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.140
version of the Boltzmann weight,
and a delta function at P

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:08.220
equals to 0 there.

00:14:08.220 --> 00:14:12.340
The rest of the
particles are up here.

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:17.070
Now, when people
saw the signature

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:22.080
of Bose-Einstein condensation,
it was precisely this.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:29.910
So this is the figure
that shows this

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:34.420
from the experiment of
Eric Cornell and group,

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:39.920
and you see two thermometers.

00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:43.420
They are cooling the
temperature of this gas

00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:46.740
of atoms that is
confined in a trap.

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:48.390
The way that they
are cooling it is

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:52.570
that they are evaporating away
the high energy particles.

00:14:52.570 --> 00:14:55.460
And then the rest
of the particles

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:58.780
are cooled down because they
thermalize, and the highest

00:14:58.780 --> 00:15:00.970
energy is always removed.

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:03.285
But in the process,
the density in the trap

00:15:03.285 --> 00:15:05.760
is also being reduced.

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:12.660
And if the density goes down,
then Tc of n will also go down.

00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:16.780
So what is plotted over here
on the right thermometer

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:21.450
is the Tc of n that you would
calculate from that formula.

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:24.160
And on the right
thermometer is actually

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:27.000
the temperature of the
particles in the gas.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.660
And you can see that
right at some point, then

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:35.390
the Tc of the particles in
the gas goes below Tc of n.

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:38.220
And what is being plotted
over here is as follows.

00:15:38.220 --> 00:15:39.740
So you have the
particles that are

00:15:39.740 --> 00:15:44.180
in the trap at some temperature.

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:49.250
We remove the trap, and then the
particles are going to escape.

00:15:49.250 --> 00:15:51.330
The particles that
have zero momentum

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:53.410
are going to stay
where they are.

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:55.480
The particles that
have large momentum

00:15:55.480 --> 00:15:57.370
are going to go further away.

00:15:57.370 --> 00:16:00.570
So let's say after one
second you take a picture.

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:03.910
And what you see over
here from the picture

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:06.930
is over here there
are the particles that

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:09.655
had most momentum
and ran further away.

00:16:09.655 --> 00:16:12.000
While at the center,
you see the particles

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.640
that had small momentum.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:17.270
You can see that always,
even at high temperature,

00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:19.910
the zero momentum is the peak.

00:16:19.910 --> 00:16:24.190
But once you go below
this condition of Tc of n,

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:28.650
in addition to the normal
peak that is over here,

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:32.210
you get some additional
peak that is appearing at P

00:16:32.210 --> 00:16:35.130
equals to 0, which is
the condensation that you

00:16:35.130 --> 00:16:39.005
have into that one single state.

00:16:39.005 --> 00:16:39.505
OK?

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:50.560
The other thing that I started
to do last time but let's

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:54.090
complete and finish
today is I wanted

00:16:54.090 --> 00:17:00.080
to show you the heat
capacity of this system.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:00.580
OK.

00:17:00.580 --> 00:17:01.690
So how do we do that?

00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:05.240
So the first
formula that we had,

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:09.869
the one that I used over here
if I were to divide by V,

00:17:09.869 --> 00:17:15.050
is that the density, in general,
is given by g over lambda

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:18.970
cubed f 3/2 plus of z.

00:17:22.710 --> 00:17:24.609
OK?

00:17:24.609 --> 00:17:29.480
And we said that if
z goes to 1, then I

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:32.770
have to interpret that
appropriately that this

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:37.570
is really just excited
states, and there's

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:41.020
going to be a separation
into the ground

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:43.340
state and the excited states.

00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:48.660
So there is really two portions
of n when we are below Tc.

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:49.210
OK?

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:52.010
But then there is also
a formula for pressure.

00:17:52.010 --> 00:18:00.480
Beta P was g over
lambda cubed f 5/2 of z.

00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:06.680
Again, these f's we had
defined-- f plus m minus 1 of z

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:11.120
was 1 over m minus 1
factorial integral 0

00:18:11.120 --> 00:18:17.470
to infinity dx x to the m
minus 1 z inverse e to the x

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:20.000
plus 1-- minus 1.

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:24.740
OK?

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:29.730
Fine.

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:33.920
But in order to calculate
the heat capacity,

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:36.520
I need to work with the energy.

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:38.560
And we said that,
quite generally,

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:41.610
whether you have
classical system,

00:18:41.610 --> 00:18:47.000
quantum gas, bosons, fermions,
the energy and pressure

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:52.680
are related simply by this
formula, which is ultimately

00:18:52.680 --> 00:18:58.470
a consequence of the scaling of
the energy being proportional

00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:03.230
to momentum squared
that we have over there.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.280
OK?

00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:10.900
So let's look at this formula.

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:11.620
What do I have?

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:19.020
For T that is less than Tc
of n, my z is equal to 1.

00:19:19.020 --> 00:19:22.820
Pressure comes
entirely from particles

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:24.900
that are moving around.

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:29.040
So although the density
breaks into two components,

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.970
in principle I guess I would
say that the pressure also

00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:34.190
breaks into two components.

00:19:34.190 --> 00:19:38.230
But the component that
is at k equals to 0

00:19:38.230 --> 00:19:39.410
is not moving around.

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:43.180
It is not giving you any
contribution to the pressure.

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:44.035
So what do we?

00:19:44.035 --> 00:19:50.460
We have P is kt, taking
