of the order of kB.

00:22:01.646 --> 00:22:05.800
You can see that this T and
this T I can cancel out.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:08.280
So I have something
that has units of kB.

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:11.940
It is extensive
proportional to volume.

00:22:11.940 --> 00:22:17.600
I can really certainly
write it in this fashion.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:24.090
And what I have
is that the curve

00:22:24.090 --> 00:22:27.881
behaves like T to the 3/2.

00:22:27.881 --> 00:22:31.130
So this is proportional
to T to the 3/2.

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:41.530
And presumably, this behavior
continues all the way

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:48.820
until the temperature at
which this system ceases

00:22:48.820 --> 00:22:51.610
to be a Bose-Einstein
condensate.

00:22:51.610 --> 00:22:55.530
So the low temperature form of
the heat capacity's calculation

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:58.840
is very simple.

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:01.530
Now, at very high
temperatures, we

00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:09.090
know that the heat capacity is
going to be 3/2 N kT, right?

00:23:09.090 --> 00:23:16.190
So ultimately, I know that if
I go to very high temperatures,

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:23.300
my heat capacity is
going to be 3/2 N,

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:28.530
if I divide it by [? kB. ?] OK?

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:32.080
Now, there is a reason
that I drew this line

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:35.160
over here less
than the peak here.

00:23:38.840 --> 00:23:44.030
Well, in order to calculate
the heat capacity on this side,

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:46.860
we'll have to do a
little bit more work.

00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:54.980
You can no longer assume
that z equals to 1.

00:23:54.980 --> 00:23:58.580
z is something
that is less than 1

00:23:58.580 --> 00:24:02.790
that is obtained by
solving N equals to g over

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:07.050
lambda cubed f 3/2 plus of z.

00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:08.770
OK?

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:12.200
But I can still presumably
use these formulae.

00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:17.670
I have that the
energy is 3/2 PV.

00:24:17.670 --> 00:24:25.760
So I have V kT times--
what is the thing

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:27.400
that I have on the
right-hand side?

00:24:27.400 --> 00:24:31.940
It is g over lambda cubed,
just as I have over here

00:24:31.940 --> 00:24:38.130
except that I have to
put f 5/2 plus of z.

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:41.100
OK?

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:44.800
And if I want to calculate
the heat capacity, what

00:24:44.800 --> 00:24:46.700
I need to do is to
take a derivative

00:24:46.700 --> 00:24:51.020
of the energy with
respect to temperature.

00:24:51.020 --> 00:24:55.790
And then I notice, well,
again, right like I had before,

00:24:55.790 --> 00:24:58.996
whatever appears here is
proportional to T to the 5/2.

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:04.950
So when I take a derivative
with respect to temperature,

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:10.850
I essentially get 5/2 this
whole quantity divided by T.

00:25:10.850 --> 00:25:14.300
So just like I had over
here, I will write the result

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:22.220
as 3/2 V kT g over lambda cubed.

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:31.290
And then I have the 5/2 1
over T of f 5/2 plus of z.

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:39.380
But you say that's the
wrong way of doing things

00:25:39.380 --> 00:25:45.680
because in addition to this
combination out front be

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:50.300
explicitly proportional
to T to the 5/2 power,

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:55.230
this factor z here is implicitly
a function of temperature

00:25:55.230 --> 00:25:59.380
because it is related to density
through that formula N equals

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:04.450
to g over lambda
cubed f 5/2 plus of z.

00:26:04.450 --> 00:26:07.760
So you should not forget to
take the derivative of what

00:26:07.760 --> 00:26:11.660
is over here with
respect to T. OK?

00:26:11.660 --> 00:26:15.110
So what do I get when I take a
derivative of this with respect

00:26:15.110 --> 00:26:16.110
to T?

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:22.230
Well, the argument
is not T, it is z.

00:26:22.230 --> 00:26:25.740
So I will have to
take a dz by dT,

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:31.100
and then the derivative of
f 5/2 with respect to z.

00:26:31.100 --> 00:26:33.500
And we saw that one
of the characteristics

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:35.860
of these functions
was that when we

00:26:35.860 --> 00:26:39.270
took the derivative
of each one of them,

00:26:39.270 --> 00:26:42.170
we generated one with
a lower argument.

00:26:42.170 --> 00:26:46.270
So the derivative would
be f 3/2 plus of z.

00:26:46.270 --> 00:26:49.200
But in order to have this
[? latter ?] property,

00:26:49.200 --> 00:26:54.900
I had to do a z d by
dz, and so I essentially

00:26:54.900 --> 00:26:59.160
need to restore
this 1 over z here.

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:05.140
So you can see that, really,
the difference between what

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:10.830
I had at low temperatures
and high temperatures,

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:15.110
at low temperatures this was
just a number that I was using

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:17.400
over here, zeta of
5/2, and I didn't

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:19.407
have to bother about
this other term.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:27.000
Now, we can figure out what
the behavior of this term

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:31.350
is certainly at
small z because we

00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:34.920
have the expansion of
these functions at small z.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:40.000
And if you do sufficient
work, you will find-- well,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.280
first of all, at the
largest values of z-- sorry,

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:46.790
at the smallest
value, z going to 0,

00:27:46.790 --> 00:27:52.150
you can confirm that the heat
capacity in units of N kB

00:27:52.150 --> 00:27:54.060
is simply 3/2.

00:27:54.060 --> 00:27:57.900
So you will come to
this line over here,

00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:02.610
and then the first correction
that you calculate you'll find

00:28:02.610 --> 00:28:06.220
is going to take you
in that direction.

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:09.730
Actually, if you do the
